Actually, looking more carefully at the lemmas:
- `bits_good` says: `e.eval.val < 2 ^ w -> assert_bits args /\ e = bits2num args`
- `bits_bad` says: `¬e.eval.val < 2 ^ w -> ¬(assert_bits args /\ e = bits2num args)`

The contrapositive of `bits_good` would give us exactly `bits_bad`. So the proof is straightforward - we just need to apply the contrapositive reasoning.

```lean
lemma bits_bad : ∀ (w : ℕ) (args : Vector (ZMod p) w) (e : Exp (ZMod p) (ZMod p)),
  (¬ e.eval.val < 2 ^ w) -> ¬ (assert_bits args /\ e = bits2num args) := by
  intros w args e h ⟨h₁, h₂⟩
  have := bits_good w args e
  simp only [h₂, and_true] at this
  exact h (this h₁)
```
